Are Women Actually Better Doctors?: The Relationship Between Female Physicians and Maternal Mortality Ratios

Olivia Atkinson

Introduction

Maternal mortality rates in the United States are among some of the highest in developed countries. In other developed countries maternal mortality rates have been steadily falling, while those in the U.S. are continuing to rise. This seems especially troubling for a country like the United States where There are a myriad of reasons given for these ever increasing statistics ranging from the increasing age of mothers to more structural issues like a broken and complicated healthcare system.

This project is particularly interested in the relationship between the maternal mortality ratios and the percentage of patients who see female doctors. The main question this paper seeks to answer is: Does seeing a female physician decrease a womans chances of dying from pregnancy related causes?

Because of gendered norms and behavior, women are understood to be more caring, attentive, and emotionally available compared to their male counterparts who are seen as aggressive, unwelcoming, and less communicative. This translates in a number of areas in social life, and I was interested to see if it would also transfer into the medical profession, as well.

Background

There have been a number of studies conducted that look at the relationship between patient care and physician gender. However, none of the studies have looked specifically at physician gender and maternal mortality.

Data and Methods

Data on maternal mortality and natality was collected from the CDC WONDER database. WONDER is an acronymn for Wide-ranging Online Data for Epidemiologic Research and provides public health data and information to the public.

this project is the maternal mortality rate by census region from the years 1999-2016.The data for Detailed Mortality - Underlying Cause of Death" is based on death certificates for U.S. residents. The detailed mortality data is compiled from data provided by the 57 vital statistics jurisdictions through the Vital Statistics Cooperative. The data set is produced by the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, National Center for Health Statistics, and the Division of Vital Statistics, Mortality Statistics Branch. (https://wonder.cdc.gov/DataSets.html)

This dataset is the breakdown of death from pregnancy related causes (maternal mortality) by census region from the years 1999-2016. This data is generalizable because it is representative of the U.S. population. The data is collected at the county-level and gives accurate descriptions of underlying causes of death.

Results

maternal mortality rate by percent of female doctors

This scatterplot shows the maternal mortality ratio by percent female physicians. As you can see, in every census region as the percent of female doctors increases so does the maternal mortality ratio. This is exactly opposite of the expected results based on priors and outside literature. However, as the next two graphs show, the results of this graph can be better udnerstood when looking at maternal mortality ratio by year and the percent of female doctors by year separately. Because both maternal mortality rates and the percentage of female doctors have been increasing when looking at the relationship together it seems as though an increase in the percent of female doctors correlates to an increase in maternal deaths.
